Mission Hill is:
Adam Jensen - Singer, Songwriter, Guitar, Piano
Alex Knutsen - Guitar
Nick DiSpagna - Bass

Mission Hill is an alternative rock band from Boston MA that mixes provoking songwriting, catchy hooks, moody vocals, an energetic live show, and strong musicianship with an unerring commitment to their unique sound. Since forming in late 2007 they have gained a large following through relentless gigging and indie distribution. Their single "Crazy" is receiving airplay all over the country and is steadily rising up the radio charts. The band has received much critical acclaim including recently being awarded an LA Music Award for "Indie Male Vocalist of the Year", being named the "Top Local Band To Watch in 2010" by Boston Music Spotlight, as well as being named to the number one spot on Alternative Addiction's list of "Top Ten Unsigned Bands in the Country".

After bursting onto the scene with their debut EP, "Mission Hill EP", the band has grown into one of the premiere bands on the New England music scene. The bands recent success is apparent with an exciting 2010 that included being selected to open for Bon Jovi and Kid Rock at Gillette Stadium, performing at the Kiss 108 Kiss Concert at the Comcast Center, completing a one month residency at the new Hard Rock Cafe in Saigon Vietnam, playing live on FOX Morning News and releasing the critically acclaimed "Beautiful Addiction EP". The band has shared the stage with many national acts including Bon Jovi, Kid Rock, Boys Like Girls, The Script, Candlebox, Vertical Horizon, Tim Reynolds, Ke$ha, Marcy Playground, WAR, Donavan Frankenreiter, Parachute, Blessid Union of Souls, The Gracious Few, and many more. With their new songs and an inspiring live performance, Mission Hill is coming for your audio souls.
summary: Great Boston Band!  Check out all of their music!

As a lifetime fan, I was unbelievably excited to hear of the release of a Chick Corea songbook.  And then I listened.  It only took me a moment before a sinking feeling set in, as I realized that ManTran, one of the best-blending and most in-tune vocal ensembles in recorded-music history, has succumbed to the scourge of modern recording known as "Auto-Tune".  Yes, Manhattan Transfer fans, welcome to the world GLEE and Cher.  It's all over the place on group harmonies, and even rears its ugly head on a few of the solo vocals.

I mean, really.  Why ON EARTH would this production choice be made?  It takes what are otherwise very hip and adventuresome arrangements, and makes them roboticized, metallic, cold, and inhuman.

I can't type any more as I'm getting angrier and angrier by the moment.  The only reason I'm giving this two stars instead of one is because of the inventiveness of the arrangements and re-interpretations of classic Corea tunes.
summary: Auto-Tune ruins what could have been ManTran's best album.  Is NOTHING sacred?

Rarely do I listen to an album over and over, and over, again.  This debut album by Nic Dawson Kelly is one of those rare occasions when the music of a new artist springs up and grabs you.  His voice is somewhat reminiscent of folk singers in earlier days.  At times his falsetto and (almost constant) vibrato is comfortably familiar, bringing back images of Donovan, Dylan, The Band, but with a distinctive English slant that cannot be said to be a purposeful 60's throw-back.  You must listen to track 4, "Marilyn".  It is a beautiful song that you just don't want to end.  The other songs are all nearly as good, notable among them, track 8, "Delicate".  The good news is: there are no fillers in the 10 track collection. With its well produced (and understated) accompaniment, (harmonic, flute, the occasional romp pianos/organs and back-beat) this record leaves you wanting more of Nic's mix of folk vocals and haunting lyrics.
Watch the movie.  You'll see why this tune touched my heart.

reviewText:
Everything you would hope for from a Scooter album and a few unexpected surprises.  The happy hardcore influence still dominates, with a few international breaks that were not in previous albums.  Scooter impresses with the new album and lets his creativity loose. Beautiful and energetic!  A raver's euphoric dream.
He builds on the sound that has already made him famous and takes it a step further by adding that international influence. It's almost like Pink Martini on speed.
Not too many reviews for the "unleaded" version. My recommendation, spend the extra money on the Dark Side Edition.  If you found yourself checking out this new album because you liked his older stuff, then you'll be thrilled with these new tunes.

Allow me to say one thing- I love Scooter. Fact is, it is GREAT dance music, and takes such huge amounts of talent. Also, with the amount of samples Scooter uses, I have been introduced into whole new worlds of music from different styles. They know what they are doing!

Now- Under The Radar Over The Top. All I have to say is... wow. What an album. At least 10 times better than Jumping All Over The World, which was damn good. So, I'll give a basic track breakdown.

Stealth- 8/10
This is just an intro track... very cool, some samples of Russian voices, etc, and then a sample which sounds a bit Sean Connery esque. Very cool intro.

J'adore Hardcore- 7/10
This was the first single from UTROTT. Albeit entertaining, this is one of the worse tracks on the album, simply because of how it matches up to the others. It's still a GREAT track, but nothing compared to the others on the album. Also, the "Dup Dup" vocals are getting a teensy bit old.

Ti Sento- 10/10
WOW. What a track! Sampling the very talented Antolenna Ruggiero of Italy, Ti Sento is a beautiful track and semi-cover version of the same song by Matia Bazar. Very exhilarating track and the vocals are top notch. Incredible! Would give it over 10 if I could... really over the top!

State of Mind- 9/10
This is where Scooter really starts to showcase that "Hardstyle" sound (Hardstyle is a fast type of electronic music with exhilarating melodies and faster beats with very cool synths.) This track has a great melody, great vocals, and is overall very enjoyable!

Where The Beats... - 10/10
By far my favorite track on the album. With an incredible melody sampled from the Italian artist Technoboy, Scooter for once uses the High Pitched Vocals in a beautiful way, making this track truly amazing. Great beat, great melody, I love this tune!

Bit A Bad Boy - 8/10
This is another good track. Not incredible, but still damn good. This song samples the intro from the SMD song "Just Like You", which in my opinion sounds a bit weird. In the original track, the opening is very emotional, but unfortunately Scooter used some sort of vocal filter and it sounds a bit off. Other than that, great melody and H.P. Baxxter's vocals are top notch again!

The Sound Above My Hair- 10/10
Another track that just makes you stop and go WOW. This was released as the 3rd single off the album, and in my opinion, the single version is better, but this version too is awesome. H.P. Baxxter actually sings for once, showing a whole new sound from Scooter. The track is very nostalgic, and has no leading synth, but that all leads to the charm and beauty of this track. This track also uses the infamous autotune effect, which has been overly criticized lately. However, tracks like this are the reason Autotune exists. Autotune was used simply for the robotic sound, making Baxxter sound great in this track.

See Your Smile- 8/10
A very fun dance track, this track has a very cool melody and a good beat. The Jumping All Over The World esque high pitched vocals return, not as well performed as they are in Where The Beats... but are still fun. The track has a nice chord progression. It's a very happy track, and a very fun one.

Clic Clac- 9/10
Back with the Hardstyle sound, Scooter makes an instrumental track that is very cool. Very interesting instrument progression, great dance song! Not much else to say, but a great track.

Second Skin- 9/10
This is a cover version of the New Wave song of the same name. It's a bit out of the spirit of the album, but it's a great track. How H.P. Baxxter sings in this track is great, there is no autotune, and it's a great synthpop track. Sounds like it came straight from the late 1980's, very interesting track!'

Stuck on Replay- 9/10
Yet another very happy track with a great synth line. The beat in the background is great for dancing, and the High Pitched Vocals are back, sampling a Lionel Ritchie song. Great song, and another very fun one.

Metropolis- 10/10
Scooter finishes the album with "Metropolis", a very well thought out trance track. The track was inspired by a DJ the band bet on Ibiza, and it makes a great finish. Yet another instrumental spare for occasional operatic sampling... very very intense track. 10/10.

TOTAL: 90/100

Conclusion- Great dance album that showcases European Electronic Music, and demonstrates that a great deal of work and thought go into the tracks. I strongly suggest you buy this, its an album that one can listen to over and over again.
Takes me back to my twenty's.

Monochromes Vol. 1 is the first volume of archival installations by the Italian multimedia duo, Rossano Polidoro and Emiliano Romanelli, performing under the moniker TU M'. The name, taken from Marcel Duchamp's same titled painting, is a French expression in which the verb is missing (tu m'...). This literally translates to "you [...] me", where the missing verb must be provided by the viewer (of the painting), or, in this case, the listener. The album, released on Richard Chartier's LINE Records, features the first four (out of nine) audio compositions, created for "two laptops, two mixing boards, two loudspeakers, one video projector, [and] one room." These pieces were recorded live at Vico Santa Chiara Studio, Citt Sant'Angelo, Italy in the summer of 2008. For the installation, the duo create an atmosphere where "sound and light vibrations reverberate inside the room, blending together in an enveloping monochrome, that creates an atmosphere to be contemplated." The visuals, available as excerpts on the TU M's website, are composed of drawn out monochrome landscapes, resembling distant mountain silhouettes and sluggish geometric figures, visible in change and movement only through sporadic skipping through the captures. Attempting careful observation, or trying to make out patterns that are not there, is futile. It's like watching yourself age in the mirror. It's like watching the clouds... The audio compositions paint the same picture. Over a slight white noise hiss and endless loops, the melody swells in ambient waves of sound, sparkling in the light of distant piano notes. Like the waves of an ocean that have been crashing against this beach for thousands of years, and many years to come, this music is new and ancient - it exists _all_ the time, somewhere completely on its own, only to be summoned into this moment with the press of a button. The sounds fade in and out with the rhythm of my breathing. Inhale soft pads. Exhale minor chords. Let this pattern wash away all worries. And when the [almost] 30 minute track ends, the melody is still there, in the background of my mind. To round off this exploration of space, sound, and light, intertwined together to create this minimal composition, the duo includes a quote by Jean Cocteau: A poet always has too many words in his vocabulary, a painter too many colors on his palette, a musician too many notes on his keyboard. Check out previous numerous releases by TU M' by rummaging through their sound and visual works, carefully catalogued on their website. Their project under the name of Steno, for example, describing themselves as "a world made up of second-hand music", is released on their own, Mr. Mutt  label, which, not coincidentally, is the name Marcel Duchamp signed on the upside down urinal, and named his found art as Fountain.

Much of the criticism I have read about Lynyrd Skynyrd's newest album is that it sounds more modern than it does old school Skynyrd. Well, this isn't old school Skynyrd, and for good reason.  There's only so many times we can listen to Free Bird and Sweet Home Alabama.  God and Guns is not their best effort, but for a new Skynyrd album in the high times of teen sensation crap, this is a most welcomed album and a delight.  Unfortunately radio stations (at least in my local area) play old school tunes from older bands. When I hear AC/DC, all I hear is Back in Black or Hells Bells (both great tunes), but I have yet to hear any station play a tune from Ballbreaker or even an older album like Flick of the Switch. When I hear Skynyrd on the radio it is always Sweet Home Alabama or the (ridiculous) radio cut of Free Bird (cutting 4-5 minutes from the song).  It's unfortunate I will never hear a tune from God and Guns because it is a solid album.  It is one of those albums that really has no "stick-out" single - by that I mean a song that stands out from the rest.  It is a better album to listen to it's entirety rather than just a single tune.

I can certainly understand those who don't like it because it isn't the Lynyrd Skynyrd you grew up with, but all bands change their tune a bit over time.  At least we still have classic bands putting out new albums in this day in age where real music is dying and YouTube crap is taking over the airwaves.
summary: It's not the old Skynyrd - and you know what, get over it

There has honestly been no question about the lackluster reaction Mariah Carey has drove in with Memoris Of An Imperfect Angel. The songs here on the album have not really been the strongest of her career, and she hasn't had that chart-strength she had shown from her past, and that has sadly shown with other divas like Beyonce', Rihanna, and the dynamic return of Whitney Houston dominating the music scene. Mariah hasn't shown that well with her last single, her cover of Foreigner's I Want To Know What Love Is, which didn't even crack the Top 40. Now, her latest single, H.A.T.E.U., the third single from her album is very weak, and tries to bring in a more simplistic feeling to her voice. Unfortunately, I wasn't appealed into the song, and it wasn't like the ballads she used to score with like Dreamlover and Through The Rain. It really was one of the weaker tracks from the album. I think Mariah should really try harder to deliver a more wide-appealing album when she does get around to it, because she really took a huge tumble on Memoirs. Hopefully, she will and hard core fans will be awaiting something better than this.

We already knew Boog could sing, but we actually get to hear Lil' Fizz's vocal skills :D. That's right, he's not rapping the whole time. But don't fret, because we get to hear him flow on the tracks as well. I think my personal favorite is Dancefloor, but all the songs are hot! They're all pretty much uptempo and they flow into eachother nicely. Fizz & Boog "Nightlife" is the start of something AMAZING!! I CANNOT WAIT TO HEAR MORE FROM THIS DUO!!!

--Melissa

reviewText: The excellence of this tune speaks for itself. The vocals, the arrangement, and the production are top drawer. This is a must have item for all serious collectors of American pop, soul, and R&B. This song will always remain a classic in every sense of the word. Great!!!
summary: JOHNNY AND JOE ARE PERFORMERS OF THE FIRST CALIBUR. THEY STILLL PERFORM TODAY. THEY LOOK AND SOUND ABSOLUTELY GREAT!!!

reviewText: As a previous reviewer commented, this is actually the band Engorged with Blood, and this is an album that was originally recorded for SOB records.  I was lucky to play bass and sing on this album, and not only is it one of my proudest musical accomplishments, it continues to be one of my favorite albums to listen to of all time.  John Hanes' songwriting is superb, Steve Kirk's blistering guitar work is tonally exquisite, Mike Simms' drumming is powerful and propulsive.  This is an album that deserves to be listened to as a whole, from start to finish, to be truly appreciated.
summary: A lost gem - one of the great albums of the '90's

reviewText: Great old song. Love it.

Daniel Smith has no more command of the bassoon than your average secondary school student, and gropes ineptly for a suitably jazzy idiom. There are reasons his performances are universally panned by professional bassoonist reviewers, and they are instantly audible to all but the most rank musical neophyte. If you want jazz bassoon, try Paul Hanson (performs with Bela Fleck), Michael Rabinowitz, or Janet Grice. Smith's horrible pitch, dreadful tone, and irregular rhythm are HIS problems, NOT the bassoon's!
I'm enjoying her album very much!
